  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>h(x)=\frac{1-x^2}{x+1}</m>. At what point(s) is <m>h</m> undefined? 
      </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        The function <m>h</m> is undefined at <m>x=-1</m>.
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution>
      <p>
        The function <m>h</m> is undefined at <m>x=-1</m>.
      </p>
    </solution>
  </task>        
  <task>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Show that the limit as <m>x</m> goes to <m>-1</m> of <m>h(x)</m> exists. Write a sentence or two about why <m>h(-1)</m> does not exist but the limit as <m>x</m> goes to <m>-1</m> does exist. 
      </p>
    </statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>h(x)=\frac{1-x^2}{x+1}=\frac{(x+1)(1-x)}{x+1}=(1-x)</m> when <m>x\neq -1</m>, so everywhere but at <m>x=-1</m> the function <m>h</m> will have output of <m>1-x</m>. Thus the limit as x goes to -1 of 1-x will be 2. Remember that the limit describes what the output of the function is approaching very near a particular input and NOT at that input. 
      </p>
    </answer>
  </task>
